an foreign-mission organization. Tree connections: Rev. Elias Cornelius (agent 1816, secretary 1831-32); Ainsworth and Harriet Ellsworth Blunt, missionaries to the Cherokee at Brainerd, Tennessee; Eliza Talcott, missionary to Japan; Rev. William Banfield Capron, Madura mission; Judge John Hooker, member."},"INST137":{"id":"INST137","primary_name":"Andover Theological Seminary","name":"Andover Theological Seminary","alt_names":["Andover Newton Theological School (post-1908 merger with Newton Theological Institution)"],"type":"theological_seminary","denomination":"Congregational","founding_year":1807,"location":{"city":"Andover","county":"Essex","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States"},"primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andover_Theological_Seminary","primary_persons":[],"hooker_connected_people":["H00703","H01354","H02539","HD1983","HD2631","I00449","I00470","T02202","I01195","H01418"],"person_ids":["X02847","X02862"],"related_institutions":[],"related_landmarks":[],"tags":[],"sources":[],"notes":"Founded 1807 as a conservative Trinitarian Congregational response to Unitarian Harvard. The most prestigious Protestant theological seminary in antebellum America. Trained ministers including Rev. John Ripley Adams (X02847, 1826), Rev. Edward Strong Dwight (HD1983), and many ABCFM missionaries. Merged with Newton Theological Institution 1908 to form Andover Newton Theological School; relocated to Newton MA. Now affiliated with Yale Divinity School (as of 2017). | Merged from INST050: Founded 1808 in Andover MA. Leading Calvinist seminary. Notable Hooker-tree connection: Rev. John Erskine Edwards (HD2631) graduated 1835."}},"crossConnections":[]}